   260→        <div class="content">
   261→            <h2>Rotated Roots of Unity and Chebyshev Polynomials</h2>
   262→
   263→            <div class="badges">
   264→                <a href="https://github.com/e-vergo/ChebyshevCircles/actions/workflows/lean_action_ci.yml">
   265→                    <img src="https://github.com/e-vergo/ChebyshevCircles/actions/workflows/lean_action_ci.yml/badge.svg" alt="CI">
   266→                </a>
   267→                <a href="https://e-vergo.github.io/ChebyshevCircles/">
   268→                    <img src="https://img.shields.io/badge/docs-passing-brightgreen" alt="Documentation">
   269→                </a>
   270→                <a href="LICENSE">
   271→                    <img src="https://img.shields.io/badge/license-Apache%202.0-blue.svg" alt="License">
   272→                </a>
   273→            </div>
   274→
   275→            <p>
   276→                When the N-th roots of unity are rotated by angle φ and projected onto the real axis and then taken to be
   277→                the roots of a polynomial, after scaling by 2<sup>N-1</sup> the polynomial formed from these projections
   278→                equals the N-th Chebyshev polynomial of the first kind plus a φ-dependent constant.
   279→            </p>
   280→
   281→            <div class="theorem-box">
   282→                <h3>Main Theorem</h3>
   283→                <div class="theorem-statement">
   284→theorem rotated_roots_yield_chebyshev (N : ℕ) (φ : ℝ) (hN : 0 < N) :<br>
   285→&nbsp;&nbsp;∃ (c : ℝ), scaledPolynomial N φ = Polynomial.Chebyshev.T ℝ N + C c
   286→                </div>
   287→                <div class="construction">
   288→                    <strong>Construction:</strong>
   289→                    <ul>
   290→                        <li>Projected roots: <code>cos(φ + 2πk/N)</code> for k = 0, ..., N-1</li>
   291→                        <li>Unscaled polynomial: <code>P(x) = ∏(x - cos(φ + 2πk/N))</code></li>
   292→                        <li>Scaled polynomial: <code>S(x) = 2<sup>N-1</sup> · P(x)</code></li>
   293→                        <li>Result: <code>S(x) = T<sub>N</sub>(x) + c(φ)</code></li>
   294→                    </ul>
   295→                </div>
   296→            </div>
   297→
   298→            <div class="visualization">
   299→                <figure>
   300→                    <img src="chebyshev_gifs/chebyshev_animation_N5.gif" alt="N=5 Chebyshev Circle Animation">
   301→                    <figcaption>
   302→                        Animation showing N=5 roots of unity being rotated. The regular pentagon (coral edges) rotates with
   303→                        the roots (red points). Vertical projection lines show how roots project to the real axis (pink points),
   304→                        which serve as roots for the blue polynomial curve. The displayed polynomial equation updates in real-time,
   305→                        showing that the curve's shape remains a 5th-degree Chebyshev polynomial (T₅(x)) while only the constant
   306→                        term <em>c</em> changes with rotation angle φ.
   307→                    </figcaption>
   308→                </figure>
   309→            </div>
